Visual encounter surveys were carried out on the 120 ha island for 3-5 days 1-5 times per year between 1991 - 2006 (excluding years 1996 and 2003-2005).
Estimated population size was estimated using the mark-and-recapture method in the 100 ha study area which was surveyed 2-4 times/week year round.
Population size was estimated from mark-and-recapture data using the POPAN platform in Program MARK. Surveys were carried out in July 1997-2009 for approximately 4 days.
Population size was estimated from mark-and-recapture data using the POPAN platform in Program MARK.Surveys were carried out in July 1997-1998 and 2003-2009 for approximately 4 days.
A systematic mark-and-recapture method was carried out over 11 consecutive field seasons between 1999-2009 for 5-50 days per year.

Mark-and-recapture methods were carried out every other day between 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.  throughout the summer months of 1969 1980 2005 2006 and 2007. Surveying was restricted to the 4.6 km research section of the North Fork of the White River. Population size was estimated using the Schumacher Eschmeyer and Chapman and Overton methods.

Mark-and-recapture using dip net and open-topped basking traps and visual surveys were carried out daily for approximately 3-4 hours in April October and early November within the 3.75 km research section of the Leaf River. The mark-and-recapture method involved capture by dip net and open-topped basking traps which were checked every hour. Population size was estimated using the NOREMARK program.

Mark-and-recapture using dip net and open-topped basking traps and visual surveys were carried out daily for approximately 3-4 hours in April October and early November within the 3.75 km research section of the Leaf River. Mark-and-recapture surveys were carried out twice a week between April - September within a 5 ha study area on West Ridge.
Burrow and transect surveys were carried out using pitfall and wire traps in the approximately 65 ha study area. Mark-and-recapture methods were employed to identify individuals in subsequent years.

Mark-and-recapture methods using Tomahawk live traps were employed on the 8.45 ha island. Burrows were monitored using infrared cameras before and after capture to ensure the majority of the population was sampled in 1984 and 2005.

Mark-and-recapture methods using Tomahawk live traps were employed on the 1.90 ha island. Burrows were monitored using infrared cameras before and after capture to ensure the majority of the population was sampled in 1984 and 2005.
Nesting beaches were monitored daily in 1996 1997 and 2000 using modified crab traps and cast nets. Population size was based on mark-recapture data and estimated using the Schnabel method.
